The image presents a graph that displays the relationship between power supply voltage and current in a circuit. The x-axis of the graph represents the voltage, while the y-axis represents the current. A line is drawn on the graph to show the trend or pattern between these two variables. The slope of this line indicates the rate at which the current changes with respect to the voltage.

The graph shows that as the power supply voltage increases, so does the current in the circuit. This relationship can be represented by a positive slope, indicating an increase in both voltage and current over time or across different points on the graph. The line connecting these two variables is steep, suggesting a strong linear relationship between them.
